 1781)].\\n\\nChemically, the human body is characterized as being composed of a limited subset of naturally occurring elements (about 25 of 92), with its composition dominated by carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen [Data: Entities (213)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Carbon and hydrogen are presented as major biological elements, with hydrogen also explicitly tied to lipids\",\"explanation\":\"Within the body-composition framing, carbon is identified as one of the four most common elements in the human body and a major constituent by mass, creating a direct bridge between the biological entity (human body) and elemental chemistry [Data: Entities (213); Relationships (159)].\\n\\nHydrogen is likewise described as biologically significant and among the four most common elements in the human body, supporting its role as a core chemical building block in biological contexts [Data: Entities (201, 213)].\\n\\nThe dataset also connects hydrogen to biomolecules by stating that hydrogen is a constituent element of lipids, reinforcing its relevance to biological macromolecular composition beyond general abundance [Data: Entities (201); Relationships (389)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Hydrogen’s chemical behavior and isotopes form a distinct subcluster connected back to broader chemistry concepts\",\"explanation\":\"Hydrogen is defined with core atomic characteristics (atomic number 1; one electron) and typical bonding behavior, including covalent bonding (H₂), and participation in common compounds such as water (H₂O), ammonia (NH₃), hydrogen chloride (HCl), and hydrogen fluoride (HF) [Data: Entities (201)].\\n\\nA key structural feature of this community is the explicit breakdown of hydrogen into three isotopic forms—protium, deuterium, and tritium—distinguished by neutron count and mass number, and represented with standard isotope notation [Data: Entities (743, 744, 745, 201); Relationships (830, 831, 832)].\\n\\nThese isotope relationships anchor a mini-network (isotope → hydrogen) that complements the valency-focused part of the graph (valency → hydrogen), showing hydrogen’s dual role as both a physical-chemistry topic (isotopes) and a chemical-combination reference point (valency reference) [Data: Relationships (830, 831, 832, 1087)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Valency is defined relative to hydrogen and used as a core rule system for constructing chemical formulae\",\"explanation\":\"Valency is defined as an atom’s combining ability relative to hydrogen, explicitly stating that hydrogen has valency 1 and serves as the reference for defining and comparing valency across elements [Data: Entities (912, 201); Relationships (1087)].\\n\\nThis establishes a dependency where understanding hydrogen (as a reference element) is foundational for understanding valency, and valency in turn is presented as a practical tool for writing chemical formulae by balancing combining powers [Data: Entities (912); Relationships (1087)].\\n\\nThe presence of a dedicated “Chemical formulae” curriculum subtopic within “Structure of matter” further situates valency and formula writing as part of a structured learning progression rather than an isolated definition [Data: Entities (151); Relationships (122)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Methane (CH4) is used as the canonical worked example linking valency to formula writing\",\"explanation\":\"Methane is explicitly introduced as an example compound formed based on valency rules: carbon has valency 4 and combines with four hydrogen atoms to produce CH₄ [Data: Entities (914); Relationships (1092)].\\n\\nThis example operationalizes valency as a balancing method for constructing chemical formulae, connecting the abstract definition of valency to a concrete formula outcome that includes hydrogen as the combining partner [Data: Entities (912, 914); Relationships (1092, 1087)].\\n\\nAs a result, methane functions as the principal illustrative bridge between the conceptual node “valency” and the applied goal of “chemical formulae,” reinforcing that valency is intended for predictive/constructive use in chemistry notation [Data: Entities (151, 914); Relationships (1092, 122)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Chemical bonding and valence electrons are presented as reinforcing concepts that underpin valency-based reasoning\",\"explanation\":\"Chemical bonding is directly linked to valency through the statement that compounds form via chemical bonds and that writing a compound’s formula requires knowing and balancing the combining powers (valencies) of the constituent atoms or ions [Data: Entities (917, 912); Relationships (1109)].\\n\\nValence electrons are also linked to valency: they are defined as electrons in the outermost energy level, and the text asserts that the number of valence electrons is generally equal to an element’s highest valency [Data: Entities (918, 912); Relationships (1108)].\\n\\nTogether, these links position valency as a central organizing concept: it is grounded in electronic structure (valence electrons) and expressed through bonding and formula construction, making it a conceptual hub within the chemistry portion of the community [Data: Relationships (1108, 1109, 1087)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Exercise-driven reinforcement indicates an instructional context, with valency as the applied competency\",\"explanation\":\"The presence of “Exercise 06” indicates an explicit practice component that applies the valency concept by asking for the valencies of several elements (lithium, carbon, calcium, sulphur, chlorine), reinforcing valency as an actionable skill rather than only a definition [Data: Entities (938); Relationships (1158)].\\n\\nThis exercise node connects to valency directly, suggesting that valency is intended as a core competency assessed or practiced within the curriculum structure that also includes “Chemical formulae” under “Structure of matter” [Data: Relationships (1158, 122); Entities (151, 912)].\\n\\nThe combined structure (definitions → worked example → exercise) reflects a pedagogical path